# Using the GridEngine to Process Data Quickly

## Overview

All the neuron-class machines are grouped together into the Sun
GridEngine (SGE), together with the old IBIC cluster (8 8-core HP z800
workstations dedicated to running batch jobs). Together these
resources are called the **IBIC neuron** cluster, or in short, the
**neuron** cluster.

As part of the cluster, you not only have priority access to your own
machine whenever you need it, but you have access to any unused cycles
on the remainder of the cluster. Computers sit idle a lot of the time,
so shared unused cycles represent a valuable resource that you can
access for free (in contrast to paying for Amazon EC2 services).

The way that this is implemented is as follows. Your own neuron-class
machines form a &quot;local&quot; queue, which belongs to you and your
group. By default, when you submit jobs, they will go to the local
queue (with some exceptions â€“ see below). Other users cannot submit
jobs to your local queue. However, you can also specify that you would
prefer to use the &quot;global&quot; queue. Jobs in the global queue
can be run on any machine in the neuron cluster. They execute at a
lower priority so that jobs that you run interactively always take
precedence, and they will be suspended (put to sleep) to make room
when jobs are submitted to the local queue. They will be awakened when
the local queue jobs complete.

In summary, the global queue is a great way to exploit compute power when you have long running but not time-critical jobs. In contrast, the local queue is guaranteed to be available to you and your group, and jobs submitted to the local queue always suspend anything else that may be running.

The remainder of this document describes how to submit parallel jobs using FSL, qsub, and make, how to select the appropriate queue, and how to submit a placeholder job to reserve your machines for non-SGE parallel jobs (e.g., MATLAB or R).

## Basics

### Certain things should be configured for you by default

First, use NX Client (or ssh -X) to log on to one of the neuron cluster workstations.

Second, ensure that your environment variables are set correctly, so that SGE commands will work. All of these should be set by default, but if they are not nothing will work correctly. Execute the following:

` env | grep SGE`


You should see the variables below among the lines returned these variables. In addition, `/opt/SGE/sge6_2u5/bin/lx24-amd64` should appear in your PATH variable.

```
SGE_CELL=default
SGE_ROOT=/opt/SGE/sge6_2u5
SGE_CLUSTER_NAME=IBIC-neuron
```


By default, if you submit jobs from the neuron machine that "you are supposed to run on", in other words, that is associated with your project, your jobs will go to the queue associated with that machine.

### Choose where to put your data for highest performance

For the SGE to be able to distribute jobs across multiple workstations
as it does, it has to be able to find each file in the same pathname
on each machine. Data in /mnt/&lt;hostname&gt; or /project_space or
/projects2 all can be accessed via the same path on all machines. You
should put your data in one of these directories.  In contrast, /tmp,
/usr/tmp, /var, and /scratch are not shared between workstations and
you will probably experience unpredictable failures if you try to
access files in those locations from scripts or software that you run
on the SGE.

However, bear in mind that data in /mnt/&lt;hostname&gt; is local to
the machine called **hostname**. Therefore, using
/mnt/&lt;hostname&gt; to store your data for a SGE job will be fastest
if you run on the local queue, especially if your job does a lot of
I/O. Examples of I/O intensive jobs are jobs that write a lot of
output files over a short amount of time. You should always run these
jobs on the local queue.

Storage on /project_space or /projects2 is appropriate for
CPU-intensive jobs that run on the global queue.

## Using the SGE to run FSL jobs in parallel

Almost all FSL commands (e.g. feat, tbss) that have multiple parts to them are written to take advantage of the SGE. However, by default this capability is disabled for debugging purposes. This is so that you can interactively run FSL commands at the terminal to make sure that your output is as expected. To enable it, type the following command:

```
export FSLPARALLEL=true 
```

Then when you run an SGE-enabled FSL command, e.g. feat, it will give you the prompt back right away because it has started the jobs on the SGE, using your local queue.

You may have a very large job to run with FSL, and wish to do so on the global queue. To specify this, you should ALSO set the environment variable FSLCLUSTER_DEFAULT_QUEUE to the name of the global queue, as shown below:

```
export FSLCLUSTER_DEFAULT_QUEUE=global.q 
```

## Using the SGE to run make jobs in parallel

The SGE can automatically parallelize jobs that are started by a
makefile. This is a useful way to structure your workflows, because
you can run the same neuroimaging code on a single core, a multicore,
and the SGE simply by changing your command line. This section assumes
that you are familar with make.

The variant of make that runs on the SGE is called qmake. If you are
using make in parallel, you will probably want to turn off FSLPARALLEL
if you have enabled it by default. Otherwise, make will submit jobs
and wait for them to finish, but instead they will be submitted to the
SGE. Make will think that they are completed, but in actuality they
will still be running in the queue. You will get errors that you have
only seen before in your dreams.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

There are two ways that you can execute qmake, giving you a lot of flexibility. The first is by submitting jobs dynamically, so that each one goes into the job queue just like a mini shell script of the type described above. To do this, type

``` 
qmake -cwd -V -- -j 20 -k all 
```

The format of this command is as follows. The flags that appear before
the -- are flags to qmake, and control gridengine parameters. The -cwd
flag means to start gridengine jobs from the current directory
(useful!) and -V tells it to pass all your environment variables
along. If you forget the -V, I promise you that (other new and
special) very bad things will happen - for example, FSL will crash
because it can&#39;t find its shared libraries. Many programs will
&quot;not be found&quot; because your path is not set correctly. On
the right side of the -- are flags to make. By default, just like
normal make, this will start exactly one job at a time. This is not
very useful! You probably want to specify how much parallelism you
want by using the -j flag to make (how many jobs to start at any one
time). This above example runs 20 jobs simultaneously. The last
argument, &quot;all&quot;, is a target for make that is dependent upon
the particular makefile used.

Parallelism with make will submit to whatever queue is most suitable for your workload. To specify a specific queue, you need to preface each recipe with the setting for SGE\_RREQ. In the code below, the Rscript code will be run on the global queue.

```
%.m1.AIC.nii.gz: %.nii.gz
        SGE_RREQ="-q global.q"; Rscript ProcessMask.R $<; 
```

We realize that modifying recipes in a Makefile is a pain and we have 
a workaround to make it easier to run makefiles on the
gridengine on whatever queue you prefer. Trevor has a beta
version of a script, &quot;rmake&quot;, that implements this
functionality.

## Other ways to submit SGE jobs

Some popular long-running software, e.g. FreeSurfer, does not have
built-in support for the SGE. However, submitting jobs by hand is
easy. To create a job, you create a small shell script for each
job. For example, to run recon-all on a subject with FreeSurfer, an
example script might look like the script below (except that I would
replace SUBJECTID with an actual subject identifier):

```
#!/bin/bash
# execute phase 1- crosssectional analysis of all time points
export SUBJECTS_DIR=/project_space/sls/freesurfer
source /usr/local/freesurfer/stable5_1/SetUpFreeSurfer.sh
recon-all -subjid SUBJECTID -all
```

If I name this script job1.sh and edit it so that SUBJECTID is the actual identifier, I can submit it to the gridengine with the following command:

```
qsub job1.sh 
```

However, in practice, if you have hundreds of subjects, it would be a pain to use an editor to create a script for each subject. If you create one template script like the one above (called &#39;template.sh&#39;) using SUBJECTID as the placeholder for the actual subject numbers, which you have listed in a file called &#39;mysubjects.txt&#39; you can do the following to submit a lot of jobs:

```
/mnt/home/ibic/bin/submit_parallel_job template.sh `cat mysubjects.txt` 
```

If you want to test this out before actually submitting the jobs, you can generate all the scripts by using the -g option (Generate only) to sls\_submit\_parallel\_job.

```
/mnt/home/ibic/bin/submit_parallel_job -g template.sh `cat mysubjects.txt` 
```

## Monitoring progress to see if jobs are complete

Now that you have submitted your jobs you might want to see where they are running. The easiest way to do this is to bring up the graphical user interface to SGE, called qmon:

```
qmon 
```

This pops up a little menu of buttons, as shown below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The upper-leftmost button is called **Job Control** , and it will open up a panel that allows you to see your **Pending Jobs** , **Running Jobs** , and **Finished Jobs**.  Pending Jobs are those that are submitted to the SGE and have not yet been scheduled to run on one of the machines in the cluster. Running Jobs are jobs that are actually running, as shown in the example below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Jobs listed in the **Finished Jobs** tab are completed. By looking to see your jobs move from Pending to Running and then to Finished, you can make sure that there are no errors in your scripts or processing that cause them to fail.

Jobs that are submitted to local queues will cause jobs on the global queue to be suspended. Suspended jobs are highlighted in pink in the display of running jobs and still appear in the job count! See how some jobs have been automatically suspended from the global queue when other jobs have come in on a local queue, below.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

You could delete these jobs listed in pink (by highlighting them and selecting the Delete button) if you don&#39;t want to wait for them to be reanimated.

Another fun thing to look at is the SGE utilization. If you click on the second button on the top left of the qmon panel, you can see the Cluster Queue Control panel. The third tab in this panel, called Hosts, lists the hosts that are in the SGE, along with the numbers of CPUs, average load, memory utilization, and CPU utilization.

## Preventing others from using your machines when you have off-SGE jobs

Sometimes you will need your neuron machine to run a job that cannot easily be submitted to the SGE (for example, a parallel MATLAB or R job, ANTs, etc). For those times, you can reserve your computing resources by submitting a placeholder job for some number of hours. During that time, your machines will run a &quot;dummy&quot; job (sleep) that will not consume resources but will prevent jobs in the global queue from being scheduled on your machines. The code below will reserve your machines for 24 hours:

```
sge_placeholder 24 
```

You can only reserve your own resources in this way. If you have an
off-SGE job that needs to run on the entire cluster, the best way to
handle that is to coordinate this by email to ibic\_sge_users@uw.edu.
